  "prompt": "What precautions were taken with Apollo 10 to ensure it did not land on the moon?",
  "response": "Apollo 10 was a critical mission in NASA's Apollo program, serving as a \"dress rehearsal\" for the first lunar landing (Apollo 11). To ensure Apollo 10 did not land on the moon, several deliberate precautions were implemented:\n\n1. **No Landing Gear**: The lunar module (LM), known as Snoopy, was deliberately not equipped with landing gear. This made it physically impossible for the spacecraft to land.\n\n2. **Reduced Fuel**: The lunar module was loaded with less fuel than required for a landing. This limited the descent capabilities and ensured the module could only perform the necessary maneuvers for approach and testing without the ability to land.\n\n3. **Mission Design**: The mission profile was designed to test all phases of a lunar landing except the actual touchdown. The LM descended to about 47,000 feet (14,000 meters) above the lunar surface before ascending back to the command module (Charlie Brown), validating critical phases such as descent orbit insertion, descent engine operation, ascent, and rendezvous.\n\nThese precautions supported Apollo 10's role in providing vital data and confidence for the subsequent Apollo 11 mission, ensuring it was ready for a safe and successful landing on the lunar surface.",
